title: For Sale:  Comment on all those angry editorials being posted!
postcontent:
Good afternoon everyone. I have never responded to anything I've read anywhere in my life, however all of the angry editorials that have been posting to this fine site recently have finally pushed me over the edge.

Many years ago in the 80's & 90's I decided to buy the American Eagle silver coins. Back then there were times when you could buy them for $4 or $5. They fluctuated with the price of silver and I always felt like investing in something tangible would be a good idea. So over 15 or 20 years - I bought a good size pile of them. Mind you I was no where near wealthy, and I'm still not, but I found a way to invest a little when I could over a long period of time. Today those same coins that cost me maybe $5000 or $6000 are worth at least $50,000 and maybe more. So if I decided to get them out of my safety deposit box tomorrow and sell them at the market rate - would I be an idiot or gouger for doing so??? Should I sell them for what I originally paid for them or risk being labeled a profiteer??

Take it one step further and suppose that some disaster (natural or otherwise) were to effect silver production and the price of silver doubled in a month (and it would) - would I be a stupid or less than upright for selling while the market was at it's peak???? So how is selling your gun any different? The way I see it is that if a man or woman who bought a Colt AR for $500 back when you could do that decided to sell it today for $2000 (because that's what it is worth now). Then I think it's a fine move and it's his right as a law abiding citizen to do so! You have to remember that by selling it he gives up his rights of ownership. Therefore if he should ever decide to buy another - he knows up front that he'll have to pay the going rate!

Heck I bought a plain jane 10-22 a few weeks ago for $375 and you know what - I was darn happy to get it! Mind you I saw them at Walmart back before Thanksgiving for $209, But I procrastinated and didn't buy it and that was STUPID on my part. I want to teach my grandson to shoot. So once again - I was delighted that someone would sell their Ruger to me even at nearly double what I would have paid a few months earlier.

I like the the vast majority of good American gun owners would much prefer that the panic being caused now by a horrible tragedy and our political appointees would have never happened in the first place! That being said however - I still thank God everyday for the hard fought freedom we all enjoy here in the good old USA! Is there anyone out there who would rather live in a place where communism or dictators reign? Where the government tells it's people who they can sell their belongings to and for how much! So think about this before posting anymore angry ads!!

Those who have rifles, pistols, ammo, etc.., and want to sell them for what they are worth - then please do so and without feeling bad about it!

Thanks for listening and God Bless the USA!!!!

p.s. no sense in emailing a response as I'm not going to read any of them. I just needed to share another viewpoint.

title: For Sale/Trade:  New information on weapons ban and what weapons they are going to ban
postcontent:
California Senator Dianne Feinstein wants 150 types of weapons banned. The Democratic Senator held a press conference to announce her lengthy gun ban bill. Some of the weapons on the list include pistols, shotguns, and rifles.

Feinstein posed with 10 weapons at her side during the Capitol Hill media event, the Daily Caller notes. New York Senator Chuck Schumer and Illinois Senator Dick Durbin stood with Feinstein during her weapons ban speech. The Assault Weapons Ban of 2013 would terminate the sale, transfer, importation, and manufacture of specific weapons.

The Assault Weapons Ban of 2013 would also ban ammunition clips which hold more than 10 rounds. While some gun control supporters feel a high-capacity magazine ban could help prevent more mass shootings, gun rights proponents largely do not agree. The average gun owner can reportedly fire and change three 10 round clips in approximately 30 seconds.

Senator Dianne Feinstein had this to say about the Assault Weapons Ban of 2013:

“Getting this bill signed into law will be an uphill battle, and I recognize that. But it’s a battle worth having.”

The proposed gun ban is more “far reaching” than the ban that expired in 2004, according to the Washington Post. Pistols and rifles that can be used with detachable or fixed ammo magazines that hold more than 10 rounds are included in Senator Feinstein’s proposed ban. Guns with “military style features” such as pistol grips, are also on the Democrat’s list.

The Assault Weapons Ban of 2013 excludes 2,250 guns used for sport of hunting purposes. Assault weapons owned legally before the potential enactment of the bill as also exempt from the ban. Unlike the previous gun ban, the 2013 ban would be permanent in nature.

The Assault Weapons Ban of 2013 list of prohibited firearms

postcontent:
Polish P-64 9x18 Makarov. The year on this is 1966

This is an absolute Cold War time piece and is amazing condition.

Barrel is just about perfect with no flaws what-so-ever.

One 6 round mag and one in the chamber makes this a 7 round conceal carry.

This does not shoot regular 9mm, it shoots 9x18 which is a larger diameter cartridge over the standard 9mm. 

For all those who seem to know more please read the following:

9x18 actually is slightly larger in diameter than 9x19. .363” vs .355”. 9x18 is generally a bit less powerful than 9x19, both in bullet weight and velocity. It’s considered the intermediate between .380 ACP (9x17) and 9x19 Parabellum. Much like 7.62x39/5.45x39 and 5.56x45, 9x18 and 9x19 were the standard cartridges between ComBloc forces and NATO forces.
